a:260:{i:0;a:1:{s:2:"id";s:19:"2391054369354649981";}i:1;a:1:{s:10:"short_code";s:11:"CEuu0fUB5F9";}i:2;a:1:{s:12:"created_time";i:1599255914;}i:3;a:1:{s:7:"caption";s:1541:"#whyoptometry üë©üèΩ‚Äç‚öïÔ∏è

Thanks @dr.hardeep.kataria for starting the conversation.

In college I volunteered at an Alzheimer's nursing home on Saturday mornings and my favorite resident to see was, let's call him, Bill. Bill had a tendency to walk around the home looking for a phone so that he could call his wife (who had passed) to make plans to see her. One day he was in a panic, he couldn't find his glasses and was looking for them desperately so that he could find a phone to call her.

Seeing how precious his sight was to him as other parts of him degenerated was it for me. I joined the pre-Optometry club at UC Irvine, volunteered¬†with Makapo, a group of paddlers with visual impairment, and conducted research in a neurobiology lab to study the relationship between the eyes and memory. I loved all of it and haven't looked back since.¬†

Building relationships with patients of all ages over time, diagnosing systemic conditions through the eyes and guiding patients to get the proper care, helping children see the world clearly so they can learn to the best of their ability are just a few of the things I love about what I do. I could go on and on and that's how I know I'm blessed. üôèüèΩ

